<gtr:region>Outside UK</gtr:region><gtr:country>Germany</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PROJECT_PARTNER</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/4D6A8C0E-1BC0-4091-80A6-1A5E0463DCB4"><gtr:id>4D6A8C0E-1BC0-4091-80A6-1A5E0463DCB4</gtr:id><gtr:name>Thales Netherland</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Haakbergerstraat 49</gtr:line1><gtr:postCode>7554 PA</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Outside UK</gtr:region><gtr:country>Netherlands</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PROJECT_PARTNER</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/F894BC5C-C71A-46AA-9CD4-2C29E76BD253"><gtr:id>F894BC5C-C71A-46AA-9CD4-2C29E76BD253</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>David</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Thomas</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/B0F881E9-2F33-45C7-B38A-7122EB46DF65"><gtr:id>B0F881E9-2F33-45C7-B38A-7122EB46DF65</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Stephen</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Greedy</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/54746839-C2BD-493A-B571-EEE96B3AAD88"><gtr:id>54746839-C2BD-493A-B571-EEE96B3AAD88</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Phillip</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Donald</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Sewell</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=EP%2FG009201%2F1"><gtr:id>975B2F1F-5640-4327-BFB2-CA67FD3239C3</gtr:id><gtr:title>Integrated Macro-models of Networks and Fields for the Simulation of Complex Systems</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>EP/G009201/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The proposal addresses a critical area in the design of complex high-speed electronic systems, namely, how to perform efficient studies of their electromagnetic behaviour in the presence of extreme geometrical, circuit and material complexity. As it is common in such cases the art is to segment the systems to subsystems and then model each one using a technique best suited to its peculiarities. Then, the various sub-models need to be combined to account fully for all interactions. This process of segmentation, sub-system modelling and aggregation is very challenging in all physical domains but it is particularly so in high-frequency applications (electromagnetic waves do not respect boundaries-they propagate and couple along large distances).In this proposal we aim to address these issues using a range of numerical models, field-based, network-based and behavioural. We combine our own expertise in constructing sophisticated macro-models of multi-scale systems with that of our partners to address a challenging problem of crucial importance to the advanced development of information and communications technologies which pervade all engineering applications. Successful completion of this research programme will make available to Industry a sophisticated hybrid modelling capability to analyse and design complex electromagnetic systems such as typified by a modern mobile phone which combines in a single handheld unit a multitude of complex functions.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/798CB33D-C79E-4578-83F2-72606407192C"><gtr:id>798CB33D-C79E-4578-83F2-72606407192C</gtr:id><gtr:name>EPSRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>433509</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The objectives of the project were: 1. Combine the efficiency and compactness of behavioural models of devices (e.g. IBIS, ICEM, RBF expansions) with the versatility, accuracy and efficiency of multi-scale features in full-field codes to produce powerful state-of-the-art hybrid models for the time-domain electromagnetic evaluation and design of high-speed systems.2. Address the issues of time-step selection for behavioural- network- and field-based parts of hybrid models to ensure maximum versatility and efficiency and to maintain stability.3. Exploit the inherent advantages of these hybrid formulations to model complex systems such as interconnected components and associated packaging.4. Interact with industrial and academic partners to explore the overlaps between EMC and SI and the methodologies required for a holistic approach to tackling concurrently both aspects of high-frequency EM design. Emphasis in this challenging objective will be on generic themes..5. Validate models and methodologies through measurements especially as regards the range of frequencies over which the different models are accurate. These objectives were attained by the following achievements..

1. Based on the TLM methodology for 3D electromagnetic field modelling embedded macro models in a 3D electromagnetic field solver of integrated circuit input and output ports based on the IBIS representation of the ports were developed. The parameters of the models can be fully defined by the industrial standard data sheets. In this way the ports of any commercial integrated circuit for with the IBIS model data is available can be incorporated into the field solver.
2. Experimental measurements have been conducted which verify the embedded macro models based on IBIS. Signal integrity measurements and chip immunity test have fully quantified the accuracy and limitations of this approach for electromagnetic compatibility studies. 
3. Embedded macro models in a 3D electromagnetic field solver (based on the TLM method) of integrated circuit input and output ports using a radial basis function representation of the ports has been developed. The parameters of the models can be fully defined by radial basis functions which provides a far more extensive representation of an integrated circuit port characteristics than the commercially available IBIS models and is therefore more suitable for electromagnetic compatibility studies. The model also includes multiport effects due to the supply and ground ports.
4. Experimental measurements have been conducted which verify the embedded macro models based on radial basis functions. Signal integrity measurements and chip immunity test have fully quantified the accuracy and limitations of this approach for electromagnetic compatibility studies.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>This work attracted and involved collaboration with the Politechnico University of Turino and the electronics company Thales of the Netherlands. It provides a powerful technique for studying signal integrity and electromagnetic compatibility on printed circuit boards with high clock speeds where full 3D electromagnetic field solvers are required as traditional circuit based simulators are not adequate. This should substantially improve the design and development times for electronic components as electromagnetic compatibility can be incorporated at the design stage rather than being addressed through costly fixes in the post fabrication stage. This should then improve the competitiveness of the electronics industry.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>0D6D9051-F680-4529-B6A8-C87D90FBD646</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Aerospace, Defence and Marine,Digital/Communication/Information Technologies (including Software),Electronics</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/23FF816A-FBBE-431F-B237-707FA02A2BC7"><gtr:id>23FF816A-FBBE-431F-B237-707FA02A2BC7</gtr:id><gtr:title>On the Integration of Behavioral Component Descriptions in the Full-wave Transmission-line Modeling Method</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/48d99f7c5e0cc1b584adb5523a732af4"><gtr:id>48d99f7c5e0cc1b584adb5523a732af4</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>I Scott</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/141E1E16-0D89-4C60-9099-A829B9D3234F"><gtr:id>141E1E16-0D89-4C60-9099-A829B9D3234F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Time-Domain Modelling of Active Electrically Fine Features in TLM</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/48d99f7c5e0cc1b584adb5523a732af4"><gtr:id>48d99f7c5e0cc1b584adb5523a732af4</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>I Scott</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/057607A5-2710-42F6-BD12-6936ADA22B20"><gtr:id>057607A5-2710-42F6-BD12-6936ADA22B20</gtr:id><gtr:title>Integration of Behavioral Models in the Full-Field TLM Method</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>IEEE Transactions on Electromagnetic Compatibility</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/25173d3ca2dbc18d6dc07948d79f47e0"><gtr:id>25173d3ca2dbc18d6dc07948d79f47e0</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Scott I</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/04CBB3FF-280C-4DDD-BE1A-FE6D1530A90B"><gtr:id>04CBB3FF-280C-4DDD-BE1A-FE6D1530A90B</gtr:id><gtr:title>Application of digital filtering techniques in three-dimensional multi-scale problems</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/46b78aa9b8eca6a524efb2bae4859cbf"><gtr:id>46b78aa9b8eca6a524efb2bae4859cbf</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Rawin V</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>978-1-4577-1014-8</gtr:isbn></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/A963C63B-953D-4057-B956-EEBBE877B9E4"><gtr:id>A963C63B-953D-4057-B956-EEBBE877B9E4</gtr:id><gtr:title>On the modeling of complex circuits using behavioral component descriptions embedded into the full-wave TLM method</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/25173d3ca2dbc18d6dc07948d79f47e0"><gtr:id>25173d3ca2dbc18d6dc07948d79f47e0</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Scott I</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>978-1-4244-5117-3</gtr:isbn></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">EP/G009201/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>DEA11FBC-BEED-4EDD-890B-97D728462D26</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>30</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Mathematical sciences</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>97B14C81-E082-430E-BC8F-733274083163</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>70</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Supercond, magn. &amp;quant.fluids</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>24D31156-9DFA-47A7-A731-E85B21A0247C</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>70</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Electromagnetics</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>CFBD6626-50CB-4AA6-8B49-9A76519BA91F</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>30</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Numerical Analysis</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>